article.description: Texas Tech beat North Dakota State on Friday night, but it was too close for Bob Knight.
article.headline: Texas Tech barely escapes N. Dakota State

inlines.body:
The Chase

Knight
Texas Tech coach Bob Knight is surpassed Dean Smith as the winningest coach in Division I men's college basketball history with Texas Tech's 70-68 win over New Mexico on Monday.

• For a look at Knight's coaching career, Click here.

article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Bob Knight's Texas Tech team won Friday night but the Hall of Fame coach was none too pleased with how the Red Raiders beat North Dakota State. "This was a game that the wrong team won," he said. "This isn't a game of brilliant decisions. This is a game of outplaying people, outhustling people, outworking people and that's what they did." Jarrius Jackson scored 26 points -- including 11 of 12 from the foul line -- to lead the Red Raiders past North Dakota State 85-81. But his defense caught the ire of Knight.

The Chase

Knight
Texas Tech coach Bob Knight is poised to surpass Dean Smith as the winningest coach in Division I college basketball history.

• For a look at Knight's coaching career, Click here.

"Jackson reverted to defense of last year," Knight said. "I'm not sure I've ever seen him play worse defensively than he did." Knight did not make players available for postgame interviews. Trailing by nine points at halftime, the Bison scored on four of their first five possessions in the second half to whittle their deficit to three, 45-42. North Dakota State went up by a point twice, the last time at 59-58 with 11:51 remaining when Ben Woodside hit a 3-pointer and two free throws. Then Tech pulled ahead for good. Jackson, who hit all three of his first-half 3-pointers, was quiet in the second half until he sank four free throws and hit field goal to end a 9-2 run that put Tech up 67-61 with 9:35 remaining. "He's a guy you got to key on all the time," Woodside said of Jackson. "We got outrebounded way too much in the first half." The Bison (1-2) got only two field goals in a five-minute span. Tech (4-0) led most of the game but the Bison opened the second half solidly. During that span, Tech committed four turnovers. Brett Winkelman and Mike Nelson scored 19 points each to lead North Dakota State. "Our kids battled until their last breath of life in that ball game," Bison coach Tim Miles said. "I thought they did a good job, but I don't like losing. It was a game I thought we could have won." Martin Zeno added 20 points for the Red Raiders. The win gave Knight his 873rd Division I career win. He is three victories shy of Adolph Rupp's 876 at Kentucky. Dean Smith stands at No. 1 with 879 wins. Tech turned offensive rebounds into 11 second-chance points in the first half. The Red Raiders used a 15-4 run late in the period, with Zeno getting seven of those points, to go up 41-32. Tech led 43-34 at halftime.
